                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="notes">
                    
                        <note n="1" xml:id="note-t-1">
                            

<p>‘Theo had fallen on the slippery street and had seriously injured his foot’, according to <rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_416">Jo van Gogh-Bonger</rs> in <hi rend="italics">Brieven</hi> 1914, p. 46. On 11 December Theo’s <rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_526">father</rs> expressed his concern: ‘We are anxious to hear what effect the water glass [sodium silicate] bandage has had, and whether you’re rid of the iron machine. But old chap! Take care! And don’t take any chances! It’s better to lie on your back yet a while than to be forced to sit any longer’ (FR b2379).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="2" xml:id="note-t-2">
                            

